a’s crafts industry struggles to adapt to its new connection to the global economy. To mediate the resulting crisis of trust, the Fair Trade sticker and other NGO aesthetics continue to successfully represent a transparent, ethical, and trusting relationship between buyer and producer. Dillon Mahoney shows that by balancing revelation and obfuscation—what is revealed and what is not—Kenyan art traders make their own roles as intermediaries and the exploitative realities of the global economy invisible.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArtisanszKenyazMombasa. 0aBusiness communicationzKenyazMombasa. 0aDigital communicationszKenyazMombasa. 0aHandicraftxTechnological innovationszKenyazMombasa. 0aHandicraftzKenyazMombasaxMarketing. 0aTourism and artzKenyazMombasa. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066755440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780520966239?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520966239423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520966239/original  a978-3-11-066755-4  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles